The paper deals with computational social choice and the complexity of manipulation in elections, which are topics that fall under the category of Game Theory (cs.GT). The use of partial preference orderings and the study of scoring rules and elimination versions of these rules suggest a focus on algorithmic decision-making and optimization, which are also relevant to Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG). The study of the exact number of candidates required for manipulation to be hard suggests a focus on computational complexity and algorithms, which are relevant to Data Structures (cs.DS). Finally, the use of the Copeland$^{\alpha}$ and maximin protocols suggests a focus on multiagent systems and distributed decision-making, which are relevant to Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA).
